04899nam a22006735i 9789048555529DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485555297 a10.1515/97890485555292doi  a(DE-B1597)649956  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aE98.M6bS73 2023 7aHIS0280002bisacsh04a299.7223/eng/202302201 aStaggs, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCalvinists and Indians in the Northeastern Woodlands /cStephen Staggs. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tList of Figures -- tNotes on Usage -- tIntroduction -- t1. “Gentiles by Nature,” 1566–1626 -- t2. “So That the Fullness of the Gentiles Might Gradually Come In,” 1627–1642 -- t3. “A Church and Community among the Christians and the Blind Gentiles,” 1642–1652 -- t4. “We, with God’s Help, Hope to Bring the Barbarous Tribes to Devotion,” 1652–1660 -- t5. “Who Gave Jacob for a Spoil and Israel to the Robbers?” 1660–1664 -- t6. “A Gentile Woman, Karanondo, … Now Called Lidia,” 1664–1750 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Dutch References to Indians: 1609–1664 -- tAppendix B. Indian Baptisms, Professions of Faith, and Marriages in the Dutch Reformed Churches of New York: 1690–1750 -- tList of Archival Sources -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Calvinists and Indians in the Northeastern Woodlands, Stephen T. Staggs analyzes the impact of the Dutch Reformation upon the cross-cultural relations between those living in and around New Netherland. Staggs shows that Native Americans and New Netherlanders hunted, smoked, ate, and drank together, shared their faith while traveling in a canoe, and slept in each other’s bedrooms. Such details emerge in documents written by New Netherlanders like Megapolensis. Author of the most accurate account of the Kanien'kehá:ka (Mohawks) by a Dutch Reformed minister, Megapolensis provides a window into the influence and limits of the Dutch Reformation upon the dynamic, multifaceted relationships that developed in the early modern Northeastern Woodlands. Megapolensis came of age when Dutch Reformed theologians looked to the Bible to incorporate Indians into a Reformed worldview. In so doing, they characterized Indians as “blind Gentiles” to whom the Dutch were being called, by God, to present the gospel through the preaching of the Bible and the Christian conduct of colonists, which necessitated social interaction. This characterization ultimately informed the instructions given to those heading to New Netherland, raised expectations among the clergy and lay chaplains who served in the colony, and prefigured the reciprocal, intimate relationships that developed between Indians and New Netherlanders during the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aIndians of North AmericaxMissions. 0aReformationzNetherlandsxInfluence. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh  aEmpire and Colonialism, Native American and Indigenous History, Atlantic History, Dutch Republic, Dutch Calvinism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048555529?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048555529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048555529/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023